body.plain:
‘These Girls’ is the fourth track in Sticky Fingers debut album, ‘Caress Your Soul’ (2013). The track offers a slice of inner turmoil and somewhat heartbreak in an accessible sound.

The lyrics describe a undeniable sense of passion  for a described porn star, by comparing her to a current girlfriend. This therefore explores the notion of desire, lust and passion. The unrequited sense of love seems to be accepted, though of significant importance.

This leads to an overall sense of inclination, craving and love, though with an underlying theme of distraught.

body.plain:
This Sticky Fingers single off their second album “Land of Pleasure” explains the effects of alcoholism and how an addicted person can dig a deeper and deeper hole whilst trying to recover from their addiction.

“The track is a real heart-wrenching ballad, unlike anything we’ve come up with before,” keyboardist Freddy Crabs says. “It’s basically about a person struggling to deal with his addiction to booze causing him to do rash things that lead him further down a path of destruction. It was written about someone we know who has found himself even more detached from his friends and loved ones and uses the drink as a way of numbing a pain that he can’t explain. A heavy topic, but I think the song does it justice.”

Seamus, the bands lead guitarist chose “Australia Street” as the song that defines their band, explaining

body.plain:
Gold Snafu, the fifth track off the Land of Pleasure album. Through this track, STIFI tell a story about their sacrifice to achieve success and their high and lows while living on the road.

In a Track by Track interview by Tonedeaf, they describe the track:

“It was a bit over a year ago when we realized; if we wanted to actually get anywhere with this band we’d have to simply give up on everything else and truly go for it. ‘Gold Snafu’ is inspired by our story so far. All the highs and lows that come with living on the road. SNAFU is a morse code term that stands for Situation Normal All Fucked Up. Gold.”

Sticky Fingers – Gold Snafu (Music Video)
Directed by Rhys Day

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-0UXhHUk6PI

body.plain:
This song is about the Soviet space dog named Laika. Laika was a stray dog wondering Moscow around 1955 when she was chosen by scientists to become the first living creature sent into space.

Before the launch, one scientist took Laika home to play with his children.

After the launch, the Soviet government claimed that Laika died when her oxygen tank ran out on day 6. However, it wasn’t until 2002 when it was revealed that she actually died 5-7 hours after takeoff due to overheating and stress.

Sputnik 2, the spacecraft, was never designed to be retrieved. Laika was always due to die. In 1988, of the scientists involved in the mission expressed is regret for sending Laika out to die.

This song features as track 8 to Sticky Fingers debut album “Caress Your Soul” released 2013.

body.plain:
Sticky Fingers are an Australian indie rock/reggae band. Formed in 2008, the band consists of frontman Dylan Frost (vocals & guitar), Paddy Cornwall (bass & vocals), Seamus Coyle (lead guitar), Beaker Best (drums & percussion) and Freddy Crabs (keys & synth).
Lead-singer Dylan Frost met bassist Paddy Cornwall and Beaker Best whilst busking in Newtown, New South Wales.



Nicknamed STIFI, their sound is a mixture or combination of reggae, psychedelic rock, and indie pop. As stated in their personal website’s biography:

… if The Clash, Pink Floyd and Arctic Monkeys are three beads of sweat that meet rolling down your back, Sticky Fingers are there licking it up.

The band has released three studio albums: Caress Your Soul, their debut album released in 2013, which reached number 39 in the Australian Albums Chart; Land of Pleasure, which peaked at number 3 on the Australian Albums Chart; and Westway (the glitter & the slums), debuting at number 1 on the Australian Albums Chart, making it the band’s first number 1 album in Australia. They’ve also released two EPs, as well as a demo EP: Extended Play, Happy Endings, and Helping Hands.

The band has gained recognition in not only Australia, but also in countries such as France, Germany, New Zealand, the Netherlands and the UK. They’ve undertaken three international tours and various national tours since forming.
